SIMPLE: pone
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pone
<hw>Pone</hw> <pr>(p⟦omac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Of Amer. Indian
origin.]</ety> <def>A kind of johnnycake.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>paune</asp>.]</altsp> <mark>[Southern U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pone</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pone
<hw>Po"ne</hw> <pr>(p⟦omac⟧"n⟦emac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>pone</ets>, imper. of <ets>ponere</ets> to place.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An original writ, now superseded by the
writ of certiorari, for removing a case from an inferior court into the
Court of Exchequer.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An obsolete writ to enforce
appearance in court by attaching goods or requiring
securities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pr>(<it>pron.</it> p⟦omac⟧n)</pr> <fld>(Card
Playing)</fld> <def>The player who cuts the cards, being usually the
player on the dealer's right.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ponent</ent>⟦br⟧
